In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October 8, 2012, as Columbus Day in the United States. He commemorates Christopher Columbus and his crew's journey to North America in 1492, acknowledging their courage and innovative spirit. The President also recognizes the indigenous peoples who inhabited the Western hemisphere and emphasizes the contributions they have made to the American experience. He highlights the pioneering Americans who have followed in Columbus's footsteps, including engineers, entrepreneurs, sailors, scientists, and explorers. President Obama also celebrates the contributions of Italian Americans and announces the Year of Italian Culture in the United States in 2013. The Congress has requested the President to proclaim the second Monday of October each year as Columbus Day. The President calls upon the people of the United States to observe this day with appropriate ceremonies and activities and directs that the flag of the United States be displayed on all public buildings in honor of the nation's diverse history.